Acronyms/Symbols CONCEPT DEFINITIONS
DIGITAL~TO~DIGITAL CONVERSION
Line Coding is the process of converting digital data to digital signals

converts a sequence of bits to a digital signal

At the sender, digital data are encoded into a digital signal; at the receiver, the digital data are recreated by decoding the digital signal
common characteristics 1. Data Element Versus Signal Element
2. Data Rate Versus Signal Rate
data element is the smallest entity that can represent a piece of information: this is the bit
signal element carries data elements

is the shortest unit (timewise) of a digital signal
data rate defines the number of data elements (bits) sent in 1 s

The unit is bits per second (bps)

aka bit rate
signal rate is the number of signal elements sent in 1 s

The unit is the baud

sometimes called the pulse rate, the modulation rate, or the baud rate
Although the actual bandwidth ofa digital signal is infinite, the effective bandwidth is finite.
*  A digital signal that carries  information is   nonperiodic. So,  bandwidth of nonperiodic signal is  continuous with  an infinite  range theoretically.
*  A digital signal that carries  information is   nonperiodic. So,  bandwidth of nonperiodic signal is  continuous with  an infinite  range theoretically.
The baud rate determines the  required bandwidth
for a  digital signal.
Baseline Wandering A long string of Os or 1s can cause a drift in the baseline (baseline wandering) and make it difficult for the receiver to decode correctly
baseline is the receiver calculates a running average of the received signal power
DC Components When the voltage level in a digital signal is constant for a while, the spectrum creates very low frequencies

These frequencies around zero, called DC (direct-current) components, present problems for a system that cannot pass low frequencies or a system that uses electrical coupling (via a transformer)

we need a scheme with no DC component.
Self-synchronization To correctly interpret the signals received from the sender, the receiver's bit intervals must correspond exactly to the sender's bit intervals

 includes timing information in the data being transmitted
Built-in Error Detection It is desirable to have a built-in error-detecting capability in the generated code to detect some of or all the errors that occurred during transmis- sion
Immunity to Noise and Interference Another desirable code characteristic is a code  I that is immune to noise and other interferences
Complexity A complex scheme is more costly to implement than a simple one. For example, a scheme that uses four signal levels is more difficult to interpret than one that uses only two levels.
Line Coding Schemes https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nkSebRJ0cG0
Unipolar Scheme all the signal levels are on one side of the time axis, either above or below.
NRZ Non-Return-to-Zero a unipolar scheme was designed as a non-return-to-zero (NRZ) scheme in which the positive voltage defines bit I and the zero voltage defines bit 0

It is called NRZ because the signal does not return to zero at the middle of the bit

main problem with NRZ encoding occurs when the sender and receiver clocks are not synchronized
Polar Schemes the voltages are on the both sides of the time axis
Non-Return-to-Zero use two levels of voltage amplitude

We can have two versions of polar NRZ: NRZ-Land NRZ- 
NRZ-L NRZ-Level the level of the voltage determines the value of the bit
NRZ-I NRZ-Invert the change or lack of change in the level of the voltage determines the value of the bit.

If there is no change, the bit is 0; if there is a change, the bit is 1.
NRZ-L and NRZ-J both have an average signal rate of N/2 Bd.
NRZ-L and NRZ-J both have a DC component problem.
RZ Return to Zero uses three values: positive, negative, and zero

the signal changes not between bits but during the bit
Biphase Manchester and Differential Manchester
Manchester encoding the idea of NRZ-L are combined into the Manchester scheme

the duration of the bit is divided into two halves

The voltage remains at one level during the first half and moves to the other level in the second half

The transition at the middle of the bit provides synchronization
Differential Manchester encoding  combines the ideas of RZ and NRZ-I

There is always a transition at the middle of the bit, but the bit values are determined at the beginning of the bi

If the next bit is 0, there is a transition; if the next bit is 1, there is none.
The minimum bandwidth ofManchester and differential Manchester is 2 times that of NRZ
Bipolar Schemes sometimes called multilevel binary

there are three voltage levels: positive, negative, and zero

 The voltage level for one data element is at zero, while the voltage level for the other element alternates between positive and negative.
AMI alternate mark inversion the word mark comes from telegraphy and means 1. So AMI means alternate 1 inversion

A neutral zero voltage represents binary 0

Binary Is are represented by alternating positive and negative voltages\

commonly used for long-distance communication but it has a synchronization problem when a long sequence of Os is present in the data.
pseudoternary the 1 bit is encoded as a zero voltage and the 0 bit is encoded as alternating positive and negative voltages.
The bipolar scheme has the same signal rate as NRZ, but there is no DC component
Multilevel Schemes to increase the data speed or decrease the required bandwidth has resulted in the creation of many schemes

goal  is  to  increase the  number of  bits  per  baud by encoding a  pattern  of  m  data elements into  a  pattern  of n  signal  elements.
mBnL schemes, a pattern of m data elements is encoded as a pattern of n
signal elements in  which 2^m less than and equal to  L^n.
2BIQ 2BIQ - two binary, one quaternary two binary, one quaternary

 uses data patterns of size 2 and encodes the 2-bit patterns as one signal element belonging to a four-level signal

 In this type of encoding m=2, n=1, and L=4 (quatemary)

used in DSL (Digital Subscriber Line) tech- nology to provide a high-speed connection to the Internet by using subscriber telephone lines.
8B6T 8B6T - 8 Binary 6 Ternary This code is used with 100BASE-4T cable

The idea is to encode a pattern of 8 bits as a pattern of 6 signal elements, where the signal has three levels (ternary)

 can have 2^8=256 different data patterns and 3^6=478 different signal patterns

478 - 256 =222 redundant signal elements that provide synchronization and error detection
4D-PAM5 4D-PAM5 - four-dimensional five-level pulse amplitude modulation four-dimensional five-level pulse amplitude modulation (4D-PAM5)

4D means that data is sent over four wires at the same time

PAM 5 means it uses five voltage levels, such as -2, -1, 0, 1, and 2

However, one level, level 0, is used only for forward error detection
8B4Q 8B4Q - 8 Binary 4 Quaternary 8 Binary 4 Quaternary

an 8-bit word is translated to a signal element of four differ- ent levels

technique is designed to send data over four channels

This scheme has a lot of redundancy in the signal pattern because 28 data patterns are matched to 44 = 256 signal patterns

The extra signal patterns can be used for other purposes such as error detection.
Block Coding
Block Coding give us this redundancy and improve the performance of line coding

block coding changes a block of m bits into a block of n bits, where n is larger than m

 ensure synchronization and to provide some kind of inherent error detecting
Block coding is normally referred to as mB/nB coding; it replaces each m~bit group with an n~bit group.
4B/5B four binary/five binary (4B/5B) was designed to be used in combination with NRZ-I
8B/10B eight binary/ten binary (8B/10B similar to 4B/5B encoding except that a group of 8 bits of data is now substituted by a 10-bit code

provides greater error detection capability than 4B/5B
Scrambling Biphase and the other scheme are not suitable for long- distance communication because of their wide bandwidth requirementand DC component.

scrambling substitutes long zero-level pulses with a combination of other levels to  provide synchronization.

two common scrambling techniques are B8ZS and HDB53.
BSZS Bipolar with S-zero substitution  is commonly used in North America
B8ZS Bipolar with 8-Zero Substitution  In this technique, eight consecutive zero-level voltages are replaced by the sequence
000VB0VB The V in the sequence denotes violation; this is a nonzero voltage that breaks an AMI rule of encoding (opposite polarity from the previous)

The B in the sequence denotes bipol_m; which means a nonzero level voltage in accordance with the AMI rule.

The letter V (violation) or B (bipolar) here is relative. The V means the same polarity as the polarity of the previous nonzero pulse; B means the polarity opposite to the polarity of the previous nonzero pulse.
B8ZS substitutes eight consecutive zeros with OOOVBOVB.
HDB3 High-density bipolar 3-zero commonly used outside of North America

In this technique, which is more conservative than B8ZS, four consecutive zero-level voltages are replaced with a sequence of 000V or B00V

maintain the even number of nonzero pulses after each substitution

The two rules can be stated as follows:

1.  If the number of nonzero pulses after the last substitution is odd, the substitution pattern will be 000V, which makes the total number of nonzero pulses even.
2.  If the number of nonzero pulses after the last substitution is even, the substitution pattern will be B00V, which makes the total number of nonzero pulses even.
HDB3 substitutes four consecutive zeros with 000V or BOOV depending on the  number of
nonzero pulses after the  last substitution.
ANALOG-TO-DIGITAL CONVERSION
PCM Pulse Code Modulation (PCM) most common technique to change an analog signal to digital data (digitization) is called pulse code modulation (PCM)

A PCM encoder has three processes:
1.  The analog signal is sampled.
2.  The sampled signal is quantized.
3.  The quantized values are encoded as streams of bits.
Sampling first step in PCM
ideal sampling pulses from the analog signal are sampled

cannot be easily implemented
natural sampling a high-speed switch is turned on for only the small period of time when the sampling occurs

The result is a sequence of samples that retains the shape of the analog signal
flat-top sampling common sampling method, called sample and hold
Sampling Rate According to the Nyquist theorem, the sampling rate must be at least 2 times the highest frequency contained in the signal.

If the analog signal is low-pass, the bandwidth and the highest frequency are the same value.

If the analog signal is bandpass, the bandwidth value is lower than the value of the maximum frequency.
Oversampling the process of sampling a signal at a sampling frequency significantly higher than the Nyquist rate
Undersampling the process of sampling a signal at a sampling frequency significantly lower than the Nyquist rate
Quantization set of amplitudes can be infinite with nonintegral values between the two limits

the process of mapping input values from a large set (often a continuous set) to output values in a (countable) smaller set, often with a finite number of elements.

Rounding and truncation are typical examples of quantization processes.
The following are the steps in quantization:     Assume the  original  analog signal has  instantaneous amplitudes
between Vmin  and Vmax.
¢    Divide the  range into  L  zones, each of  height Δ  (delta)
Δ= (V_min  -    V_max) /L
e    Assign quantized values  of  0  to  L-1  to  the  midpoint of each zone
¢ Approximate the value of the sample amplitude to the quantized values.
Quantization Levels depends on the range of the amplitudes of the analog signal and how accurately we need to recover the signal

In audio digitiz- ing, L is normally chosen to be 256; in video it is normally thousands

Choosing lower values of L increases the quantization error if there is a lot of fluctuation in the signal.
Quantization Error error created in the quantization process

the inherent uncertainty in digitizing an analog value as a result of the finite resolution of the conversion process.

Quantization error depends on the number of bits in the converter, along with its errors, noise, and nonlinearities.
Encoding last step in PCM

After each sample is  quantized and the number of bits  per sample is  decided, each sample can  be changed to  an  n,-bit code word.
Original Signal Recovery recovery of the original signal requires the PCM decoder
PCM Bandwidth lf  we digitized the signal, whatis the new bandwidth of the
channel?
Delta Modulation developed to reduce the complexity of PCM

finds the change from the previous sample
Modulator used at the sender site to create a stream of bits from an analog signal

builds a second signal that resembles a staircase
Demodulator takes the digital data and, using the staircase maker and the delay unit, creates the analog signal
TRANSMISSION MODES
Parallel Transmission By grouping, we can send data n bits at a time instead of 1

The mechanism for parallel transmission is a conceptually simple one: Use n wires to send n bits at one time.

advantage of parallel transmission is speed

significant disadvantage: cost
Serial Transmission one bit follows another, so we need only one communica- tion channel rather than n to transmit data between two communicating devices

advantages are only one communication channel, serial transmission reduces the cost

Serial transmission occurs in one of three ways: asynchronous, synchronous, and isochronous.
Asynchronous transmission is so named because the timing of a signal is unimportant

Instead, information is received and translated by agreed upon patterns. As long as those patterns are followed, the receiving device can retrieve the information without regard to the rhythm in which it is sent.
In asynchronous transmission, we send
1   start bit  (0)  at  the  beginning and 1   or more stop bits  (1s)  at the end of each
byte. There may be a  gap between
each byte.
Asynchronous here means
asynchronous at the byte level, but the bits are still synchronized;
their durations are the same.
Synchronous Transmission the bit stream is combined into longer "frames," which may contain multiple bytes

data are transmitted as an unbroken string of 1s and Os, and the receiver separates that string into the bytes, or characters, it needs to reconstruct the information.
In  synchronous transmission, we send
bits  one after another without start or stop bits  or gaps. It  is  the responsibility
of the  receiver to  group the  bits.
Isochronous Transmission  is a data transfer system that sends blocks of data asynchronously. In other words, the data stream can be transferred at random intervals. 

is also known as START-STOP mode or CHARACTER mode. Each character or byte is framed as a separate and independent unit of DATA that may be transmitted and received at irregular and independent time intervals.
